2026-03-26 | Equal Partition with One Optional Cell Removal

	Question
Return true if such a partition exists.

	Approach
1.	Compute total sum of grid.
2.	We try all possible cuts:
		- horizontal cuts  
		- vertical cuts  

3.	For each cut:
		let sum1 = left/top part  
		sum2 = total - sum1  

4.	If sum1 == sum2 → return true  

5.	Otherwise:
		diff = abs(sum1 - sum2)

6.	We need to check:
		can we remove a cell with value = diff from the larger section?

7.	To do this efficiently:
		- maintain frequency maps while scanning  
		- track elements in current partition  

8.	If such element exists → return true  

9.	If no cut works → return false  

	Time Complexity
	O(m × n)

	Space Complexity
	O(m × n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    bool check(vector<vector<int>>& grid, bool horizontal) {

        int m = grid.size(), n = grid[0].size();
        long long total = 0;

        for(auto &row : grid)
            for(int x : row)
                total += x;

        unordered_map<int,int> rightFreq;

        for(auto &row : grid)
            for(int x : row)
                rightFreq[x]++;

        unordered_map<int,int> leftFreq;

        long long curr = 0;

        if(horizontal){

            for(int i=0;i<m-1;i++){

                for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
                    curr += grid[i][j];
                    leftFreq[grid[i][j]]++;
                    rightFreq[grid[i][j]]--;
                    if(rightFreq[grid[i][j]]==0)
                        rightFreq.erase(grid[i][j]);
                }

                long long other = total - curr;

                if(curr == other) return true;

                long long diff = abs(curr - other);

                if(curr > other){
                    if(leftFreq.count(diff)) return true;
                } else {
                    if(rightFreq.count(diff)) return true;
                }
            }
        }
        else{

            for(int j=0;j<n-1;j++){

                for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
                    curr += grid[i][j];
                    leftFreq[grid[i][j]]++;
                    rightFreq[grid[i][j]]--;
                    if(rightFreq[grid[i][j]]==0)
                        rightFreq.erase(grid[i][j]);
                }

                long long other = total - curr;

                if(curr == other) return true;

                long long diff = abs(curr - other);

                if(curr > other){
                    if(leftFreq.count(diff)) return true;
                } else {
                    if(rightFreq.count(diff)) return true;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }

    bool canPartitionGrid(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {

        return check(grid, true) || check(grid, false);
    }
};

	Key Insight
If sums are unequal, we only need to remove **one element equal to the difference** from the larger side.  

Using frequency maps allows us to check this efficiently while scanning cuts, keeping the solution optimal at **O(m × n)**.
